narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: labor supply and income taxation, dynamic discrete choice model and its estimation, income process and partial insurance, collective labor supply model and its estimation, search model and its estimation, human capital development and measurement error
Methodologies and topics in labor economics and other related fields.
I was able to attain knowledge related to the labor market and the marriage market. Also, I was able to gain insight into structural models. Very useful.
I learn the tools used in labor economics and also the literature that is currently in the frontier.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strength: Fairly broad areas in labor economics Weakness: Partly because of that, I couldn't find the relationship between the areas.
I believe there should be more lessons devoted to understand the structural models and trying to put them in practice, like trying to replicate a paper.
Nice overview of the literature, discussion of main issues. Maybe covering less topics in greater depth would be better.
It will be helpful sometimes to know which paper to read in advance

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If you want to do labor in the Yale, you have to take this course. It certainly gives you the broad understanding on the labor economics literature. However, the explanation is not necessarily always clear, so you have to read the paper and have an understanding to some degree and have concrete questions in mind when you attend the class.
Definitely. I gained a lot of insight into labor topics.
Definitely, very nice (and demanding) course in the area.
I will totally recommend the course to any student interested in labor economics
